<p><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-302709" src="https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite-620x964.png" alt="comparison chart: Hootsuite and Facebook Business Suite" width="620" height="964" srcset="https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite-620x964.png 620w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite-310x482.png 310w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite-768x1194.png 768w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite-988x1536.png 988w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Hootsuite-vs-FB-business-suite.png 1122w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>
<p>Hootsuite&#8217;s Facebook scheduler also has a <strong>Best Time to Publish</strong> feature that comes up with personalized recommendations for when you should post, based on your account&#8217;s historical performance. The system suggests times specific to your goals (building brand awareness, boosting engagement or increasing sales), setting your posts up for the best visibility and performance possible.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-large wp-image-272575" src="https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/hootsuite-product-updates-2021-q1-best-time-to-post-620x459.png" alt="screenshot showing Hootsuite's publishing suggestions feature, which tells you the best time to post" width="620" height="459" srcset="https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/hootsuite-product-updates-2021-q1-best-time-to-post-620x459.png 620w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/hootsuite-product-updates-2021-q1-best-time-to-post-310x229.png 310w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/hootsuite-product-updates-2021-q1-best-time-to-post-768x568.png 768w, https://blog.hootsuite.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/hootsuite-product-updates-2021-q1-best-time-to-post.png 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" /></p>
<p>With Hootsuite, you can also <a href="https://blog.hootsuite.com/how-to-bulk-schedule/">bulk-schedule up to 350 posts at once</a>. Think of all the time this could save you!</p>
<h2><strong>5 tips for scheduling Facebook posts</strong></h2>
<p>Whether you use a Facebook scheduler like Hootsuite or schedule posts directly on Facebook, you should follow these best practices:</p>
<h3><strong>1. Always stay on brand</strong></h3>
<p>When scheduling posts, the pressure to post immediately is off. So take the time to craft relevant content that will land with your audience.</p>
<p>Scheduling posts can also help you keep your brand guidelines in mind when composing weeks or months-worth of content. Make sure that your campaigns across Pages and even social networks are aligned with yours and your audience’s values.</p>
<h3><strong>2. Carefully choose the publication date and time </strong></h3>
<p>Avoid posting when your audience isn’t online. Hootsuite&#8217;s Facebook scheduler comes with a<a href="https://www.hootsuite.com/platform/analyze"> Best Time to Publish feature</a> that will help you schedule Facebook posts on days and at times when your audience is active on the platform.</p>
<p>The more people see your Facebook updates, the more opportunity there is to generate engagement, drive traffic and gain potential new followers.</p>
<h3><strong>3. Know when to pause your Facebook posts</strong></h3>
<p>Don’t forget about the posts you’ve scheduled. Always consider how current events or crises could change the meaning and tone of the posts you wrote well before those events — they may become irrelevant or insensitive in ways you simply could not have predicted.</p>
<p>Regularly check in on your scheduled posts to keep track of what’s coming up. That way, you can pause or delete scheduled posts before they’re published, and avoid any potential backlash.</p>
<h3><strong>4. Remember that you can’t schedule <em>everything</em></strong></h3>
<p>Some things you have to post about in real-time. And some types of posts cannot be scheduled at all. On Facebook, these include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Facebook events</li>
<li>Facebook check-ins</li>
<li>Photo albums</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>5. Track analytics and engagement</strong></h3>
<p>A good posting schedule shouldn’t be based on guesswork. You’ll know what works best for your Facebook audience by monitoring your performance in a <a href="https://blog.hootsuite.com/social-media-analytics/">social media analytics tool</a>.</p>
<p>Historical data will show you what posts perform well, and where you could make improvements.</p>
<p><strong>Use Hootsuite to schedule all of your social media posts, engage with your followers, and track the success of your efforts. Sign up today.</strong></p>
